{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a171fb7f-993a-4010-8e33-b839d84d49ff","content":"You're on **MSTest 3.8.2** / .NET 9. Here's the modern pattern:\n\n### Constructor injection for `TestContext` + sync init, `[TestInitialize]` for async init\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests\n{\n    private readonly TestContext _testContext;\n    private MyService _service;\n\n    // Constructor: inject TestContext + synchronous setup\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        _testContext = testContext;\n        _service = new MyService();\n    }\n\n    // Async setup (constructors can't be async)\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public async Task InitAsync()\n    {\n        await _service.ConnectAsync();\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public async Task MyTest()\n    {\n        _testContext.WriteLine(\"Running test...\");\n        // ...\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- **Constructor injection** of `TestContext` is the modern MSTest v3 approach (replaces the old `public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }` property pattern).\n- Use the **constructor** for synchronous setup and field initialization.\n- Use **`[TestInitialize]`** for async setup — C# constructors can't be `async`.\n- Similarly, use **`[TestCleanup]`** for async teardown.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"766ab8a9-5a97-4ab0-b725-7e6179c34e56","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"They're using MSTest 3.8.2 on .NET 9.0. Let me provide guidance on the modern MSTest approach.\n\nIn MSTest v3, the recommended way to:\n\n1. **Inject TestContext**: Use constructor injection (`public MyTestClass(TestContext testContext)`). The old `public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }` property-based approach still works but constructor injection is the modern pattern.\n\n2. **Synchronous initialization**: Use the constructor or `[TestInitialize]` method.\n\n3. **Asynchronous initialization**: Use `[TestInitialize]` with an async method. Note that constructors can't be async, so `[TestInitialize]` is the way for async setup.\n\n\n4. **Class-level vs test-level setup**: `[ClassInitialize]` runs once per class while `[TestInitialize]` runs before each test. For TestContext injection and async setup, `[TestInitialize]` is the preferred approach in v3.8.2 since constructor injection handles the sync case and `[TestInitialize]` handles async scenarios.","outputTokens":665,"requestId":"1042:527BE:3896317:3E5724F:6A02ED02"},"id":"5a913069-ba44-419e-a6b2-783837e99a79","timestamp":"2026-05-12T09:04:21.107Z","parentId":"c3a35267-5a86-421a-9ffe-a0d90563d909"}
